COMMUNITY members in Alexandra, north of Joburg marched against the rise of inequality on Tuesday.According to an Oxfam report released on Monday, the gap between the ultra-rich and the poor remains large even after over 20 years of democracy in Mzansi.Thembinkosi Dlamini, manager of economic justice at Oxfam South Africa, told Daily Sun they were trying to mobilise the community to pay attention to issues of inequality.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The release of the report and the community’s drive coincide with the World Economic Forum’s meeting in Davos, Switzerland.Dlamini said they chose Alexandra because it was close to Sandton, known for being the richest square mile in Africa. “This is where the effects of inequality are clearly visible,” he said.